\f0\fs24 \cf0 Oscar Fingal O\'92Flahertie Wills Wilde died at the turn of the century, three years after his prison sentence for gross indecency with men came to an end. In the 46 years of life that preceded his early death, Wilde took on the project of allowing his public perception, professional career, and literary life to work with and against one-another, in the pursuit of 
\i creating 
\i0 himself through this nexus.\
\
This is, without a doubt, a contentious point. And it\'92s easy enough to say that we are essentially what we do, and how we seem, or whatever we made and how it seemed to make us seem, etc. The ontological question is worthless in this sense, because what made Wilde stand out was the intent that went behind this process of creation.\
\
His fascination with image and public perception was ahead of its time. To this day he is remembered through various anecdotes, most of which consist of one-liners he gave to acquaintances and journalists. \'93No. I have nothing to declare\'85except my genius\'94, he told the customs official as he entered America.\
\
It might seem frivolous, even aggravating to think that Wilde could\'92ve potentially sowed the seeds of a purely aesthetic lifestyle, one that sees public perception, or lack thereof (in the case of however many enigmatic public figures we have now), as a vehicle to creating the ultimate 
\b career. 
\b0 Oscar Wilde, is without a doubt, a forerunner in this notion of playing out an entire life so that it culminates in this way. \
\
Artists like David Bowie, even Kanye West, find themselves under this tradition as well, of course, the question loops back not from an ontological position, but from a position of intent. 
\i Did they actually live out their entire lives as art? 
\i0 If it didn\'92t start that way, a cognizance appeared soon enough. It\'92s no surprise that artists like this are defined through eras, with their creations acting as bookends. \
\
For Wilde, a relatively easy way to break down his life is through his aesthetic beginnings, his theatrical career, and the untimely and tragic years that led to his death. This is, of course, discounting his fruitful journalistic career.\
\
His life as an aesthete, a devotee to the purely aesthetic lifestyle, begun before he found literary success, but he was, nonetheless, well known. One person who saw the potential in Wilde\'92s public persona early on was Richard D\'92Oyly Carte, who organized a North American lecture tour for him.\
\
Immediately he was bombarded not with questions about his aesthetic project, but about seemingly frivolous aspects of his personal life. What he slept in, how he enjoys his baths, trims his fingernails, etc. Hilariously enough, these in-themselves 
\i were 
\i0 questions about his aesthetic project, and proved its sweeping success in the immediate goal of capturing everyone\'92s gaze. Still, his life and goals as an aesthete were far from over. It\'92s important to note that Wilde was never interested in this vanity as a means for fame and nothing else, he was on a mission, the lectures themselves prove it.\
\
Take, for instance, when an attendee in one of his lectures asked if the reports of him parading around London carrying a lily were true. \'93It\'92s not whether I did it or not that\'92s important, but whether people believed I did it\'94.\
\
Wilde continued on this path and translated it into a journalistic career, bookended by the publication of 
\i The Picture of Dorian Gray, 
\i0 in the July 1890 edition of 
\i Lippincott\'92s Monthly Magazine.\
