The Picture of Dorian Gray 
\i0 tells the story of a beautiful young man named Dorian, who\'92s being painted by his friend Basil. Basil\'92s friend, Lord Henry, perhaps one of the most quotable characters in English literature, has a talk with Dorian, revealing 
\i just 
\i0 how intense the nature of Dorian\'92s beauty truly is, a notion Dorian himself didn\'92t even realize until now. Horrified, or perhaps merely sad, Dorian stares at Basil\'92s creation, and envies the everlasting beauty the painting will have, a stark contrast to the material aging Dorian will undoubtedly face.\
\
This is an Oscar Wilde novel, so it\'92s no surprise that vanity would overthrow physics, and a slew of other scientific facets of the world. Dorian stays beautiful and young, the image old. In fact, the image seems to change, and morph into a far more disturbing image of its subject as Dorian plunges deeper into hedonism, taking advantage of his eternal beauty.\
