These two works, written five years apart, highlight Wilde\'92s artistic maturity and set the stage for the philosophical aspects of his aesthetic lifestyle.\
\
From 1895-onward, Wilde\'92s life found its biggest challenges. His prosecution against John Douglas, the Marquess of Queensberry and father of Wilde\'92s lover, Lord Alfred Douglas, came after years of tension. In a now infamous story, The Marquess left his calling card at Wilde\'92s club, proclaiming him to be a sodomite. Wilde\'92s prosecution for libel turned tragically against himself, and led to the revelation that Wilde was, in fact, engaged in a number of homosexual liaisons. He was handed a warrant for his arrest, and spent two years in prison.\
